WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.077 --> 00:00:00.889
Voiceover: Before we get started,

00:00:00.889 --> 00:00:03.099
I've got to tell you
about 3 great companies.

00:00:03.099 --> 00:00:04.721
PicClick is the first.

00:00:04.721 --> 00:00:08.632
It's a one-person startup from
my friend Ryan in San Diego.

00:00:08.632 --> 00:00:11.869
PicClick gives you a
visual way to search Ebay,

00:00:11.869 --> 00:00:13.599
Etsy, and other sites.

00:00:13.599 --> 00:00:17.229
Ryan is already doing 1
million product sales per month

00:00:17.229 --> 00:00:18.933
on PicClick.com.

00:00:18.933 --> 00:00:21.003
Not hits, but sales.

00:00:21.003 --> 00:00:26.435
Go to picclick.com to
see how he's doing it.

00:00:26.435 --> 00:00:29.653
99designs, it's the largest
crowdsource marketplace

00:00:29.653 --> 00:00:31.134
for graphic design.

00:00:31.134 --> 00:00:33.068
When I used them, I wrote a description

00:00:33.068 --> 00:00:35.492
of the design I needed, and
how much I wanted to pay.

00:00:35.492 --> 00:00:37.342
I got a bunch of designs back.

00:00:37.342 --> 00:00:39.108
I gave each designer feedback.

00:00:39.108 --> 00:00:41.274
I picked the one I liked best,

00:00:41.274 --> 00:00:43.237
and that's the only one that I paid for.

00:00:43.237 --> 00:00:44.902
Try them for logo design.

00:00:44.902 --> 00:00:46.544
If you need a blog designed, use them.

00:00:46.544 --> 00:00:49.243
If you need app icons, use them.

00:00:49.243 --> 00:00:50.641
There's so many different reasons

00:00:50.641 --> 00:00:51.908
why you might want to use them.

00:00:51.908 --> 00:00:54.402
Check out 99designs, and you'll see

00:00:54.402 --> 00:00:59.223
why so many past mixergy
guests have used 99designs.com

00:00:59.223 --> 00:01:00.486
And Grasshopper.

00:01:00.486 --> 00:01:03.504
I've had them now as my
longest sponsor for a reason.

00:01:03.504 --> 00:01:05.820
Not only does my audience love them,

00:01:05.820 --> 00:01:07.913
but you might have heard
several guests here, on Mixergy,

00:01:07.913 --> 00:01:09.920
say that they use Grasshopper.com

00:01:09.920 --> 00:01:11.421
as a result of these messages,

00:01:11.421 --> 00:01:13.336
and they love it.

00:01:13.336 --> 00:01:16.587
It's the virtual phone system
that entrepreneurs like me love

00:01:16.587 --> 00:01:18.840
because it offers us multiple extensions,

00:01:18.840 --> 00:01:20.506
music on hold, call forwarding.

00:01:20.506 --> 00:01:23.783
It gives you an impression
of having a big,

00:01:23.783 --> 00:01:25.526
professional organization,

00:01:25.526 --> 00:01:30.015
but also caters to your need
to travel and to be flexible.

00:01:30.015 --> 00:01:32.000
Check out Grasshopper.com.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:33.275
Here's the program.

00:01:33.781 --> 00:01:34.947
Andrew: Hey, everyone. It's Andrew Warner,

00:01:34.947 --> 00:01:37.821
founder of Mixergy.com, home
of the ambitious upstart.

00:01:37.821 --> 00:01:39.690
I've got with me today Salman Khan.

00:01:39.690 --> 00:01:43.005
He is the founder of,
well, an online school

00:01:43.005 --> 00:01:46.002
that's launched and run
largely through YouTube.

00:01:46.002 --> 00:01:47.567
Do I have that right?

00:01:47.567 --> 00:01:48.353
Sal: Yeah.

00:01:48.353 --> 00:01:51.196
Well, it's known mainly
for the video library

00:01:51.196 --> 00:01:52.121
on YouTube right now.

00:01:52.121 --> 00:01:53.567
There's 1,500 videos.

00:01:53.567 --> 00:01:55.771
It is being used,

00:01:55.771 --> 00:01:59.833
it's had over 16 million views,
200,000 unique users a month.

00:01:59.833 --> 00:02:03.534
It is definitely the most used
education platform on YouTube,

00:02:03.534 --> 00:02:05.308
and as far as I can tell,

00:02:05.308 --> 00:02:07.197
looking at the other
open course intiatives,

00:02:07.197 --> 00:02:09.833
the most used library
on the web right now.

00:02:09.833 --> 00:02:11.745
Andrew: I went through
the courses in preparation

00:02:11.745 --> 00:02:15.107
for this interview, and I saw
that you teach math, basic math.

00:02:15.107 --> 00:02:18.468
You say you start out
teaching 1 plus 1 equals 2.

00:02:18.468 --> 00:02:23.100
I got so into a history course,
that I almost stopped working,

00:02:23.100 --> 00:02:24.763
and I said, "Andrew, you can't do this."

00:02:24.763 --> 00:02:25.857
So you know what I did?

00:02:25.857 --> 00:02:28.015
I used this program called Zamzar,

00:02:28.015 --> 00:02:29.307
that's gonna rip your course.

00:02:29.307 --> 00:02:30.996
It's gonna put it on my iPhone.

00:02:30.996 --> 00:02:34.313
I'm going over to an
estancia here this weekend.

00:02:34.313 --> 00:02:36.951
On the ride over, I'm gonna be
watching you teach me history.

00:02:36.951 --> 00:02:39.123
It was that freakin' fascinating.

00:02:39.123 --> 00:02:40.305
Salman: Oh, cool. I'm glad.

00:02:40.305 --> 00:02:42.110
That's actually really good feedback

00:02:42.110 --> 00:02:43.620
because I get a lot of,

00:02:43.620 --> 00:02:45.358
there's a lot of
interesting discussion about

00:02:45.358 --> 00:02:48.106
how credentialed someone should
be to teach a certain subject,

00:02:48.106 --> 00:02:50.066
and most of my credentials
are in computer science

00:02:50.066 --> 00:02:52.800
and in finance and math,

00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:55.154
I did the history. I love history,

00:02:55.154 --> 00:02:59.169
but I did that one, to kind
of push the boundaries,

00:02:59.169 --> 00:03:01.343
to show that you don't have
to necessarily have a PhD,

00:03:01.343 --> 00:03:02.921
you just have to have a
passion for the subject,

00:03:02.921 --> 00:03:03.757
so I'm glad to hear that.

00:03:03.757 --> 00:03:05.909
You hopefully won't have to rip it soon.

00:03:05.909 --> 00:03:07.553
It'll be on iTunes by
the end of the summer.

00:03:07.553 --> 00:03:10.652
It'll be on iTunes U, the
entire Khan Academy library.

00:03:10.652 --> 00:03:11.765
Andrew: I'm gonna come back to that point

00:03:11.765 --> 00:03:13.467
that you said you don't
have to have a PhD.

00:03:13.467 --> 00:03:16.200
I want to ask you about
what qualifies you to teach

00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:17.027
all these subjects,

00:03:17.027 --> 00:03:18.565
because you're teaching
more and more of them.

00:03:18.565 --> 00:03:20.953
You've got a course on how IPOs work,

00:03:20.953 --> 00:03:24.483
on how to raise money
for a startup, all that.

00:03:25.083 --> 00:03:26.737
But let me start off asking you a question

00:03:26.737 --> 00:03:28.880
that I ask a lot of my other guests here.

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:33.321
How much money does the Khan Academy make?

00:03:33.321 --> 00:03:34.815
Salman: Well, that answer could be,

00:03:34.815 --> 00:03:37.230
it could be answered on a
bunch of different levels.

00:03:37.230 --> 00:03:38.673
It is a not-for-profit.

00:03:38.673 --> 00:03:40.566
That's a decision we can talk about

00:03:40.566 --> 00:03:42.400
because there was kind
of a thought process.

00:03:42.400 --> 00:03:44.557
I was being approached by some people

00:03:44.557 --> 00:03:46.563
in the venture capital and
the entrepreneurial world

00:03:46.563 --> 00:03:50.146
about starting it as kind of
either a social for-profit venture

00:03:50.146 --> 00:03:52.463
or a pure for-profit venture
or a little bit of both.

00:03:52.463 --> 00:03:54.500
But it is a pure not-for-profit.

00:03:56.191 --> 00:03:57.895
There's a little bit of
advertising that comes in

00:03:57.895 --> 00:04:00.028
and goes to the not-for-profit,

00:04:00.443 --> 00:04:02.665
and we're being very delicate
about the advertising,

00:04:02.665 --> 00:04:04.001
not too agressive there.

00:04:04.001 --> 00:04:06.842
When I quit my job as a hedge
fund analyst in September,

00:04:06.842 --> 00:04:09.299
I was making nothing, so I was
essentially living off of savings,

00:04:09.299 --> 00:04:13.417
and very recently-

00:04:13.417 --> 00:04:18.587
Andrew: Sorry, the video just
cut out right after you explained

00:04:18.587 --> 00:04:20.539
that you quit your job
as a hedge fund analyst.

00:04:20.801 --> 00:04:22.430
Can you pick it up from there?

00:04:22.430 --> 00:04:22.933
Salman: Oh, yeah.

00:04:22.933 --> 00:04:26.015
So, after I quit, I was
living off of savings

00:04:26.015 --> 00:04:28.968
until about, I would
say, about a month ago,

00:04:28.968 --> 00:04:33.015
where we've gotten some
fairly significant donations,

00:04:33.015 --> 00:04:36.271
so now I can at least
take a salary to do this.

00:04:36.271 --> 00:04:38.316
Not a hedge fund salary, but a salary.

00:04:38.316 --> 00:04:39.682
(both laugh)

00:04:39.682 --> 00:04:41.967
Andrew: The donations
are coming from people

00:04:41.967 --> 00:04:45.770
who are hitting that donate
button on top of your website?

00:04:45.770 --> 00:04:47.188
Salman: Well, you know,
there's a ton of people

00:04:47.188 --> 00:04:50.042
who are hitting that little
PayPal donation, you know,

00:04:50.042 --> 00:04:51.095
and that's anywhere from,

00:04:51.095 --> 00:04:53.979
I've gotten donations as
little as 50 cents all the way,

00:04:53.979 --> 00:04:56.995
but there's a lot of people
who just donate unsolicited,

00:04:56.995 --> 00:04:59.030
100, 200, 300, 500.

00:04:59.030 --> 00:05:01.096
I've even gotten a couple
that were 2-3 thousand

00:05:01.096 --> 00:05:03.047
just from that PayPal donation button.

00:05:03.047 --> 00:05:05.599
But more recently, we've gotten
some pretty significant checks

00:05:05.599 --> 00:05:09.134
from people out here in
the Valley that, you know,

00:05:09.134 --> 00:05:12.351
get us to the point that I
have a runway to have a salary

00:05:12.351 --> 00:05:13.846
for at least several years.

00:05:13.846 --> 00:05:17.399
Obviously, there'll be other
opportunities to backfill from there.

00:05:17.399 --> 00:05:19.318
Andrew: What kind of people?

00:05:22.131 --> 00:05:25.029
Salman: A couple of them are
venture capitalists in this area.

00:05:25.029 --> 00:05:26.583
One gentleman, he's a,

00:05:26.583 --> 00:05:27.265
actually, he's not in the Valley.

00:05:27.265 --> 00:05:27.888
He's in Europe.

00:05:27.888 --> 00:05:30.420
He's a pretty prominant
businessman in Europe.

00:05:30.420 --> 00:05:31.351
There's another,

00:05:31.351 --> 00:05:34.391
I mean, a lot of the people
are people in the tech space.

00:05:34.391 --> 00:05:37.528
You know, they're not doing it
as an investment, obviously.

00:05:37.528 --> 00:05:40.373
It's a not-for-profit, but I
think they're excited about

00:05:40.373 --> 00:05:43.665
the potential here, the
potential for kind of disrupting.

00:05:43.665 --> 00:05:46.335
I think the feedback I
get from a lot of them is,

00:05:46.335 --> 00:05:48.038
look, a lot of people are doing this,

00:05:48.038 --> 00:05:50.761
a lot of people have talked
about doing this type of thing.

00:05:50.761 --> 00:05:53.587
It's kind of an obvious idea to
take videos from good instructors,

00:05:53.587 --> 00:05:54.533
put them on the web,

00:05:54.533 --> 00:05:56.418
and eventually do some
analytics around it,

00:05:56.418 --> 00:05:57.477
do some self-paced learning,

00:05:57.477 --> 00:05:59.169
and everything's gonna be great,

00:05:59.169 --> 00:06:00.922
but no one's really done it.

00:06:00.922 --> 00:06:03.757
The best to date outside of Khan Academy

00:06:03.757 --> 00:06:06.676
is the open courseware
efforts at MIT and Stanford

00:06:06.676 --> 00:06:07.468
and all of that.

00:06:07.468 --> 00:06:10.703
That's essentially been
just videos and classrooms.

00:06:10.703 --> 00:06:12.505
Andrew: Boring.

00:06:12.905 --> 00:06:13.805
Can I say that?

00:06:14.389 --> 00:06:15.311
Salman: You can say it.

00:06:15.311 --> 00:06:17.132
I feel the ...

00:06:17.132 --> 00:06:21.252
I'm a huge consumer of
their open courseware,

00:06:21.252 --> 00:06:22.586
but you have to be really motivated

00:06:22.586 --> 00:06:25.075
and sit through a lot of things

00:06:25.075 --> 00:06:26.670
that you don't necessarily
want to pay attention to

00:06:26.670 --> 00:06:28.253
to get to what you want.

00:06:28.253 --> 00:06:30.460
Sometimes it's delivered
well, sometimes it's not.

00:06:30.460 --> 00:06:32.421
It's kind of inconsistent quality,

00:06:32.421 --> 00:06:33.696
and there's all sorts of
other things that occur

00:06:33.696 --> 00:06:34.951
when you have a video
camera in a classroom

00:06:34.951 --> 00:06:36.924
that make it a little bit weird.

00:06:37.877 --> 00:06:39.588
I think they appreciate the fact

00:06:39.588 --> 00:06:45.261
that Khan Academy is 99%
execution and 1% talk.

00:06:45.891 --> 00:06:47.179
Andrew: Let me ask you this, then.

00:06:48.317 --> 00:06:49.995
I got your resume here.

00:06:49.995 --> 00:06:52.517
I actually went to the way-back machine

00:06:52.517 --> 00:06:54.857
to see what you were up
to before you did this,

00:06:54.857 --> 00:06:56.242
to see who you were,

00:06:56.242 --> 00:06:57.506
and you had your resume up.

00:06:57.506 --> 00:06:59.595
I'm looking at it. Pretty
frickin' impressive.

00:06:59.595 --> 00:07:01.572
In addition to 3 degrees from MIT,

00:07:01.572 --> 00:07:03.773
which a lot of us have seen
in news stories about you,

00:07:03.773 --> 00:07:05.516
and the one from Harvard.

00:07:05.516 --> 00:07:08.599
You worked at Oracle. You
worked a venture capital firm.

00:07:08.599 --> 00:07:09.948
You worked for,

00:07:09.948 --> 00:07:11.197
you were on a path to be

00:07:11.197 --> 00:07:14.370
one of these rich people
of Silicon Valley.

00:07:14.370 --> 00:07:16.854
You're not gonna be that now, right?

00:07:16.854 --> 00:07:18.250
Not through this.

00:07:18.250 --> 00:07:21.136
Salman: Yeah, unless they make a movie

00:07:21.136 --> 00:07:23.808
about the Khan Academy, I won't.

00:07:25.730 --> 00:07:27.123
Yeah, you know, it's funny.

00:07:27.123 --> 00:07:28.292
When I was working at a hedge fund,

00:07:28.292 --> 00:07:29.927
the six years after business school,

00:07:29.927 --> 00:07:31.845
I was a senior analyst at a hedge fund,

00:07:31.845 --> 00:07:35.542
and it was doing well, and
then my manager retired.

00:07:35.542 --> 00:07:36.929
He encouraged me to start my own fund,

00:07:36.929 --> 00:07:40.625
so I was on that track to kind
of be a hedge fund manager

00:07:40.625 --> 00:07:44.206
and all of that, but the whole
time, I kind of rationalized

00:07:44.206 --> 00:07:46.131
that the only reason why I'm doing this

00:07:46.131 --> 00:07:49.475
is because I want to
one day start a school.

00:07:49.475 --> 00:07:51.330
In my mind, I didn't
want to start a school,

00:07:51.330 --> 00:07:53.884
write grants and go to the
department of education

00:07:53.884 --> 00:07:55.677
and get a charter and all of that.

00:07:55.677 --> 00:07:56.965
I felt it would constrain me too much.

00:07:56.965 --> 00:07:59.210
I was like, no, I just
want to become really rich

00:07:59.210 --> 00:08:00.489
and just do it on my own terms.

00:08:00.489 --> 00:08:01.657
That was my rationalization

00:08:01.657 --> 00:08:04.165
for just trying to generate
alpha day and night.

00:08:05.026 --> 00:08:06.996
But, as the Khan Academy story goes,

00:08:06.996 --> 00:08:08.763
I kind of got an outlet
for some of my ideas

00:08:08.763 --> 00:08:10.876
with my cousins, tutoring them virtually,

00:08:10.876 --> 00:08:12.927
and then the YouTube thing took off.

00:08:12.927 --> 00:08:14.029
I wrote a little software app.

00:08:14.029 --> 00:08:15.390
A lot of people are using that

00:08:15.390 --> 00:08:17.895
and a lot of the vision
started to become concrete

00:08:17.895 --> 00:08:19.760
a lot sooner than I'd expected it to,

00:08:19.760 --> 00:08:23.327
and then it was just kind of
a little bit of introspection,

00:08:23.327 --> 00:08:26.835
realizing that I got a lot
more satisfaction out of,

00:08:26.835 --> 00:08:29.975
the hedge fund job, it is a great job,

00:08:29.975 --> 00:08:31.340
even irrespective of how much they

00:08:31.340 --> 00:08:32.623
may or may not compensate you,

00:08:32.623 --> 00:08:35.008
but this was just 10 times more fun.

00:08:35.008 --> 00:08:40.977
Just the impact, everything
I did on a daily basis,

00:08:40.977 --> 00:08:44.206
it kind of added to this library
that could be around forever.

00:08:44.206 --> 00:08:45.691
My son who's 15 months old right now

00:08:45.691 --> 00:08:48.699
could use it when he's
18 or 30 or whenever.

00:08:49.391 --> 00:08:50.671
That idea got really exciting,

00:08:50.671 --> 00:08:53.488
and just when you think about it,

00:08:53.488 --> 00:08:55.199
and you see people in
the Valley like this.

00:08:55.199 --> 00:08:57.798
I think Silicon Valley
is an interesting place,

00:08:57.798 --> 00:08:59.133
because you do see this.

00:08:59.133 --> 00:09:00.397
It really isn't about money.

00:09:00.397 --> 00:09:01.548
I think so many people,

00:09:02.362 --> 00:09:04.213
they view the money as points,

00:09:04.213 --> 00:09:05.535
and they view it as kind of a

00:09:05.535 --> 00:09:08.929
how important was my
contribution to the world,

00:09:08.929 --> 00:09:10.881
and I think with Khan Academy,

00:09:10.881 --> 00:09:14.547
I get to do that without having
to play the whole, you know,

00:09:15.577 --> 00:09:17.102
venture-backed startup game,

00:09:17.102 --> 00:09:19.588
and what's interesting
about Khan Academy is

00:09:19.588 --> 00:09:21.764
even though it's not
gonna make me any money,

00:09:21.764 --> 00:09:24.360
and I'm not gonna be able to
buy a nice house in Atherton

00:09:24.360 --> 00:09:26.156
and all of that type of thing,

00:09:26.156 --> 00:09:28.740
in terms of just impact,
it is already, kind of,

00:09:28.740 --> 00:09:32.142
it's getting more
notoreity than many already

00:09:32.142 --> 00:09:33.802
fairly successful startups.

00:09:33.802 --> 00:09:34.555
If I had entered the startup world

00:09:34.555 --> 00:09:36.719
and I had an exit for 10
or 20 million dollars,

00:09:36.719 --> 00:09:38.757
that's a huge win, but
those type of things are

00:09:38.757 --> 00:09:40.302
a dime a dozen out of the Valley,

00:09:40.302 --> 00:09:41.389
and the Khan Academy,

00:09:41.389 --> 00:09:42.591
it's not like I'm, that's my,

00:09:42.591 --> 00:09:44.689
the Khan Academy, I already
feel has more impact

00:09:44.689 --> 00:09:50.289
than a lot of these, so
from that point of view,

00:09:50.289 --> 00:09:54.242
it was just way more impact, way more fun.

00:09:54.242 --> 00:09:56.321
Every day, the things
that I was contributing,

00:09:56.321 --> 00:09:59.079
I felt it was contributing
to kind of a lasting legacy,

00:09:59.079 --> 00:10:02.358
and just the letters you get from people.

00:10:02.911 --> 00:10:04.197
This was also another realization.

00:10:04.197 --> 00:10:07.139
When you work at a firm,
kind of the best thing

00:10:07.139 --> 00:10:08.561
that could happen to you is
kind of a pat on the back

00:10:08.561 --> 00:10:10.724
from the boss, or a nice bonus,

00:10:10.724 --> 00:10:15.081
but in this, I'm getting
letters, like 20 or 30 a day.

00:10:15.081 --> 00:10:16.932
These letters, some of
them are just thank you,

00:10:16.932 --> 00:10:19.711
but some of them are like,
"I was gonna fail algebra

00:10:19.711 --> 00:10:21.659
"until I started using these videos,"

00:10:21.659 --> 00:10:23.533
or, "Now I want to be an engineer,

00:10:23.533 --> 00:10:25.146
"and I thought I was bad
at math my whole life."

00:10:25.146 --> 00:10:27.308
When you get stuff like that,
it really makes you say,

00:10:27.308 --> 00:10:29.942
"Hey, this is what I want to do."

