00:19:55.333 --> 00:19:56.312
Because I was kind of telling him about,

00:19:56.312 --> 00:19:57.406
"Yeah, you know, these kids,

00:19:57.406 --> 00:19:58.954
"I keep having to do the
same lecture over again.

00:19:58.954 --> 00:20:00.137
"It's getting hard to schedule.

00:20:00.137 --> 00:20:02.198
"I have 5 or 10 kids
that I'm working with,

00:20:02.198 --> 00:20:03.484
"and I have a day job."

00:20:03.484 --> 00:20:04.531
He was like, "Why don't
you make YouTube videos?

00:20:04.531 --> 00:20:06.104
"It might be useful for them."

00:20:06.104 --> 00:20:10.821
So I tried it out, and the initial
feedback I got from my cousins

00:20:10.821 --> 00:20:14.556
was that they liked me better
on YouTube than in person,

00:20:14.556 --> 00:20:16.710
or virtually, or live,

00:20:16.710 --> 00:20:20.566
and I think the takeaway
was it was less-stress,

00:20:20.566 --> 00:20:22.401
they could pause and repeat.

00:20:22.401 --> 00:20:23.954
They could do it on their own time,

00:20:23.954 --> 00:20:25.737
there was none of this
scheduling situation,

00:20:25.737 --> 00:20:27.470
so I got that feedback from them.

00:20:27.470 --> 00:20:29.814
Other people started watching the videos,

00:20:30.121 --> 00:20:32.903
and other people started
sending these notes,

00:20:32.903 --> 00:20:34.868
like, "Hey, I got an A on my algebra exam

00:20:34.868 --> 00:20:36.233
because of this," and at
first, it might have been

00:20:36.233 --> 00:20:37.445
one note a week or one note a month,

00:20:37.445 --> 00:20:39.066
but it got me pretty excited.

00:20:39.066 --> 00:20:41.509
The ideas started to crystallize,

00:20:41.509 --> 00:20:43.492
I said, "Gee, if I make this library,

00:20:43.492 --> 00:20:45.883
"even if it's just useful to my family,

00:20:45.883 --> 00:20:47.509
"like my cousins who are using it now,

00:20:47.509 --> 00:20:49.230
"and my, I didn't have a son at the time,

00:20:49.230 --> 00:20:52.217
"but my future kids, and anyone else,

00:20:52.217 --> 00:20:54.768
"that's just a huge gift to our family,

00:20:54.768 --> 00:20:56.165
"and if other people end up using it,

00:20:56.165 --> 00:20:57.786
"that's even more neat,"

00:20:57.786 --> 00:20:59.616
so it kind of became a fun outlet for me.

00:20:59.616 --> 00:21:00.930
I was working, you know,

00:21:00.930 --> 00:21:04.623
we had moved out to Palo
Alto a year after that,

00:21:04.623 --> 00:21:06.141
so I was working east coast hours,

00:21:06.141 --> 00:21:07.868
so I was done with work by about 2 p.m.

00:21:07.868 --> 00:21:09.702
My wife was in medical residency,

00:21:09.702 --> 00:21:13.287
so I had a lot of time, and as
this was a fun use of my time,

00:21:13.287 --> 00:21:15.608
and it was kind of an outlet for
me to get this kind of education,

00:21:15.608 --> 00:21:17.787
these educational ideas off my plate,

00:21:17.787 --> 00:21:19.326
and I love mathematics.

00:21:19.326 --> 00:21:21.358
It was also a way to
engage parts of my brain

00:21:21.358 --> 00:21:23.724
that I hadn't engaged in a while,

00:21:23.724 --> 00:21:25.210
so it was just a lot of fun,

00:21:25.210 --> 00:21:26.536
and it was actually having an impact.

00:21:26.536 --> 00:21:30.791
Then fast forward 4 years, you know,

00:21:30.791 --> 00:21:32.837
September 2009, take it from there,

00:21:32.837 --> 00:21:36.178
and now we have, whatever,
16-17 million views

00:21:36.178 --> 00:21:38.613
and it's the most used
open course library.

00:21:38.613 --> 00:21:40.622
Andrew: September 2009
being the day you quit,

00:21:40.622 --> 00:21:42.910
being the month you quit your work

00:21:42.910 --> 00:21:44.070
so that you can do this full time?

00:21:44.070 --> 00:21:45.140
Salman: Right.

00:21:45.140 --> 00:21:46.931
Andrew: You know what I'm
wondering as you're saying this?

00:21:46.931 --> 00:21:49.200
If I had a relative who
wanted to learn math

00:21:49.200 --> 00:21:51.943
or wanted to learn anything,
I might help them once.

00:21:51.943 --> 00:21:54.237
Then after that, I might
refer them to a website

00:21:54.237 --> 00:21:57.221
where they can go and learn after that.

00:21:57.221 --> 00:21:59.275
Why would you spend so much time?

00:21:59.998 --> 00:22:03.447
You've got a job, you've
got other things going on.

00:22:03.447 --> 00:22:06.406
Salman: Well, you know, I think it's ...

00:22:06.406 --> 00:22:08.337
You know, it was fun.

00:22:08.598 --> 00:22:10.660
Look, if you work at a hedge fund,

00:22:10.660 --> 00:22:11.747
it was a great job, and I have to say,

00:22:11.747 --> 00:22:13.802
the hedge funds I worked for,

00:22:13.802 --> 00:22:15.816
and I worked for one hedge
fund in particular for 6 years,

00:22:15.816 --> 00:22:19.499
it wasn't the typical really
high-power type-A type place.

00:22:19.499 --> 00:22:22.325
It was a really intellectual,
thoughtful type of firm.

00:22:22.325 --> 00:22:24.463
My boss was a really great
guy who really focused on

00:22:24.463 --> 00:22:25.673
kind of work-life balance.

00:22:26.611 --> 00:22:29.822
But, at the same time,
it was a really good job,

00:22:29.822 --> 00:22:31.443
but there wasn't a lot that you could say,

00:22:31.443 --> 00:22:33.506
what have I contributed
to the world today?

00:22:34.982 --> 00:22:37.932
Even the nature of the
hedge fund job itself,

00:22:37.932 --> 00:22:38.837
you could do really good analysis

00:22:38.837 --> 00:22:40.132
and then that investment goes nowhere,

00:22:40.132 --> 00:22:41.626
and then you could get
lucky, and you could do,

00:22:41.626 --> 00:22:42.830
so there's a lot of that,

00:22:42.830 --> 00:22:46.998
and you almost crave for
something that you do every day,

00:22:46.998 --> 00:22:49.400
where you feel like I
did this for X hours,

00:22:49.400 --> 00:22:53.331
and that X hours was a positive
contribution to something.

00:22:53.331 --> 00:22:56.129
It made the pie a little bit bigger,

00:22:56.129 --> 00:22:58.719
and I think that's what gave
me a little bit of purpose,

00:22:58.719 --> 00:23:00.679
and it gave me an outlet,

00:23:00.679 --> 00:23:03.213
and it made me feel
like I wasn't, you know.

00:23:03.213 --> 00:23:06.279
I talked to a lot of my friends
who are roughly at my stage

00:23:06.279 --> 00:23:07.456
in my career, and I was like, you know,

00:23:07.456 --> 00:23:08.674
it kind of dawned on me that look,

00:23:08.674 --> 00:23:10.644
you're life is pretty valuable,

00:23:10.644 --> 00:23:12.997
and what I was doing at the hedge fund,

00:23:12.997 --> 00:23:16.044
I don't want to demean it.
I think it's a great job,

00:23:16.044 --> 00:23:18.309
but I'd spent 6 years of my life,

00:23:18.309 --> 00:23:20.275
but really what I had to show for it was

00:23:21.674 --> 00:23:24.656
I had experience, I learned
to analyze securities better,

00:23:24.656 --> 00:23:26.891
and I saw a lot about how
businesses work and all of that,

00:23:26.891 --> 00:23:29.390
but what I really had to show
for it was just some numbers

00:23:29.390 --> 00:23:31.208
in a bank account someplace.

00:23:31.208 --> 00:23:33.391
It's like I really had no
actual tangible contribution

00:23:33.391 --> 00:23:35.720
to show for it, and
this gave me that outlet

00:23:35.720 --> 00:23:37.687
where I felt like these
years weren't wasted.

00:23:38.102 --> 00:23:40.075
I feel that more and more.

00:23:40.075 --> 00:23:42.242
Evey day, I almost feel
like my day is wasted

00:23:42.242 --> 00:23:43.560
if I don't make a few videos,

00:23:43.560 --> 00:23:44.810
or if I don't write a
little bit of software.

00:23:44.810 --> 00:23:46.234
If I just sit a whole day in meetings

00:23:46.234 --> 00:23:48.888
or if I'm trying to
fundraise or whatever else,

00:23:48.888 --> 00:23:51.056
I feel like I'm not doing
what the Khan Academy

00:23:51.056 --> 00:23:52.837
is supposed to be doing.

00:23:52.837 --> 00:23:55.302
Andrew: Did you think at the
time that this might help

00:23:55.302 --> 00:23:57.893
you prepare for the school
you'll launch some day,

00:23:57.893 --> 00:23:59.613
or did you think that
maybe this would lead to

00:23:59.613 --> 00:24:02.449
a school or software that
I can create and sell?

00:24:02.449 --> 00:24:03.956
What did you think it
was going to lead to?

00:24:03.956 --> 00:24:06.714
Salman: Once it got to about,

00:24:06.714 --> 00:24:12.163
once the JavaScript
modules, once I had about,

00:24:12.163 --> 00:24:13.588
I would say about 20 of them,

00:24:13.588 --> 00:24:16.923
and I was using it with my
cousins and family and friends,

00:24:16.923 --> 00:24:17.702
and they were using it,

00:24:17.702 --> 00:24:19.827
it really was teaching them,

00:24:19.827 --> 00:24:21.838
and you combine it with the videos.

00:24:21.838 --> 00:24:23.379
Once the video library got to about 100,

00:24:23.379 --> 00:24:25.806
and the combination of
it really was pretty good

00:24:25.806 --> 00:24:30.152
at teaching people
pre-algebra through algebra,

00:24:30.152 --> 00:24:31.726
I started to think very
seriously, you know what?

00:24:31.726 --> 00:24:33.881
The school fo the future needs to have

00:24:33.881 --> 00:24:36.491
something like this as
its operating system,

00:24:36.491 --> 00:24:38.051
needs to have something
like this at its DNA.

00:24:38.051 --> 00:24:42.580
I did, and actually I do
view, this virtual school

00:24:42.580 --> 00:24:46.035
that we talked about earlier,
as, it is a virtual school.

00:24:46.035 --> 00:24:46.949
It could stand on itself.

00:24:46.949 --> 00:24:48.447
People could go to that virtual school

00:24:48.447 --> 00:24:50.762
and use it to learn things,

00:24:50.762 --> 00:24:51.631
independent of anything else,

00:24:51.631 --> 00:24:55.278
but it could also be used
as the operating system

00:24:55.278 --> 00:24:57.258
or the DNA for a physical school,

00:24:57.258 --> 00:24:59.366
where you have a 1-room schoolhouse,

00:24:59.366 --> 00:25:00.870
kids of all ages,

00:25:00.870 --> 00:25:02.094
you know, you don't,

00:25:02.094 --> 00:25:04.938
it's actually a very bizarre
way that people connect age

00:25:04.938 --> 00:25:06.198
with different concepts,

00:25:06.198 --> 00:25:09.905
so you have students of all
ages in a room together.

00:25:09.905 --> 00:25:11.594
They're working on, for part of their day,

00:25:11.594 --> 00:25:13.104
not their full day, for part of their day,

00:25:13.104 --> 00:25:17.556
they're using technology to kind
of get their core skills going.

00:25:17.556 --> 00:25:18.465
If they don't understand something,

00:25:18.465 --> 00:25:20.161
there are other people in the
room that are going to help them,

00:25:20.161 --> 00:25:21.624
so you have a lot of peer to
peer occurring in the room.

00:25:21.624 --> 00:25:23.483
It could even occur across site,

00:25:23.483 --> 00:25:25.049
and then the rest of the day is spent

00:25:25.049 --> 00:25:26.760
doing real project-based learning.

00:25:26.760 --> 00:25:28.289
There's a lot of talk about
project-based learning,

00:25:28.289 --> 00:25:31.472
but not much of it is substantive.

00:25:31.472 --> 00:25:32.572
I mean, real project-based learning,

00:25:32.572 --> 00:25:33.931
where kids are actually
learning to program,

00:25:33.931 --> 00:25:35.525
like they're really
working, building things.

00:25:35.525 --> 00:25:38.168
They're actually writing things
that are being published.

00:25:38.168 --> 00:25:40.074
They're actually composing music

00:25:40.074 --> 00:25:41.349
instead of just learning to play music.

00:25:41.349 --> 00:25:42.310
That's the whole aspect.

00:25:42.310 --> 00:25:45.406
I definitely, I definitely
wanted this to become,

00:25:45.406 --> 00:25:48.717
eventually the, and it does
seem like it is becoming

00:25:48.717 --> 00:25:51.105
the DNA of a possible framework in school.

00:25:51.105 --> 00:25:53.222
I did it with a couple of summer camps,

00:25:53.222 --> 00:25:56.391
and the teachers wanted reports.

00:25:56.391 --> 00:25:58.615
Can I see, you know, all the
students, where they are,

00:25:58.615 --> 00:26:01.598
and we pretty quickly settled
on that kind of a paradigm,

00:26:01.598 --> 00:26:02.945
when the teacher would walk into the room,

00:26:02.945 --> 00:26:04.881
all the kids are working
at their own pace,

00:26:04.881 --> 00:26:07.296
and the teacher just gets
a spreadsheet saying,

00:26:07.296 --> 00:26:09.576
"Look, everyone's fine, but
those 2 kids are having trouble

00:26:09.576 --> 00:26:13.312
"with adding and subtracting
negative numbers."

00:26:13.312 --> 00:26:15.807
Instead of the teacher giving a
lecture and all of that type of stuff,

00:26:15.807 --> 00:26:16.487
and admit,

00:26:16.487 --> 00:26:18.538
the teacher just takes
those two kids aside,

00:26:19.491 --> 00:26:20.808
does a very intimate session with them,

00:26:20.808 --> 00:26:21.965
and let everyone else
work at their own pace.

00:26:21.965 --> 00:26:23.407
Then, who are the next
two people who need help?

00:26:23.407 --> 00:26:25.399
You could even, before the
teacher even gets involved,

00:26:25.399 --> 00:26:26.597
you could have other peers helping,

00:26:26.597 --> 00:26:27.516
all that type of thing,

00:26:27.516 --> 00:26:29.141
so you can get more and
more technology in it,

00:26:29.141 --> 00:26:30.442
you could get more and more data on it,

00:26:30.442 --> 00:26:32.691
you can make everyone's
life a lot more streamlined,

00:26:32.691 --> 00:26:34.565
and be able to do much
more intelligent things

00:26:34.565 --> 00:26:37.073
on where you point people's energies.

00:26:38.119 --> 00:26:40.145
Andrew: I could so see the
passion as you talk about this.

00:26:40.145 --> 00:26:42.912
I can't imagine you were this
passionate about hedge funds

00:26:42.912 --> 00:26:45.932
or venture capital or
any of the previous work.

00:26:45.932 --> 00:26:49.464
Salman: Yeah, no, I was not.

00:26:49.464 --> 00:26:50.908
I could see now that I'm not
working in those industries,

00:26:50.908 --> 00:26:51.870
I can say it.

00:26:51.870 --> 00:26:53.140
(Sal laughs)

00:26:53.140 --> 00:26:56.774
You have to, I mean, those were,

00:26:56.774 --> 00:26:59.245
I mean, I think outside
of the Khan Academy,

00:26:59.245 --> 00:27:02.206
my job at the hedge fund was
probably the best possible job.

00:27:02.206 --> 00:27:03.833
What was fun about it,
as you mentioned earlier,

00:27:03.833 --> 00:27:06.631
I teach out of my core competency,

00:27:06.631 --> 00:27:09.696
so a lot of what I do is
I really learn new things

00:27:09.696 --> 00:27:11.608
and I try to learn it
at a really deep level

00:27:11.608 --> 00:27:13.756
and that's really what I had
to do at my hedge fund job,

00:27:13.756 --> 00:27:15.720
where every day, we'd
talk to an oil company,

00:27:15.720 --> 00:27:16.174
and then the next day,

00:27:16.174 --> 00:27:18.631
we'd talk to an internet
marketing company,

00:27:18.631 --> 00:27:22.791
and the next day, we'd talk
to a chicken egg company,

00:27:22.791 --> 00:27:24.194
so it was this kind of process of

00:27:24.194 --> 00:27:25.468
you're always learning new things,

00:27:25.468 --> 00:27:27.164
and you have to kind of
become a quick expert.

00:27:27.748 --> 00:27:29.089
Andrew: I see.

00:27:30.165 --> 00:27:32.127
All right, so you get these videos online.

00:27:32.127 --> 00:27:33.699
I understand how today, when you have,

00:27:33.699 --> 00:27:36.240
how many videos do you have?

00:27:37.239 --> 00:27:38.685
Salman: A little over 1,500.

00:27:38.685 --> 00:27:39.662
Andrew: A little over 1,500.

00:27:39.662 --> 00:27:42.859
I understand when you get
to even 500 to 1,000 videos.

00:27:42.859 --> 00:27:44.276
It starts to feel like something.

00:27:44.276 --> 00:27:45.756
When NPR comes and interviews you,

00:27:45.756 --> 00:27:47.061
when the BBC has you on,

00:27:47.061 --> 00:27:48.660
starts to feel like something.

00:27:48.660 --> 00:27:52.470
What about when it was just 100 or 200?

00:27:52.470 --> 00:27:53.826
Did you ever feel at those moments,

00:27:53.826 --> 00:27:55.628
wow, I'm just a YouTube producer.

00:27:55.628 --> 00:27:57.834
It's me and the guy who's
creating the cat videos,

00:27:57.834 --> 00:28:00.217
and he's got more viewers than I do.

00:28:00.217 --> 00:28:01.200
Salman: Oh, yeah.

00:28:01.200 --> 00:28:02.037
No, absolutely.

00:28:02.037 --> 00:28:04.410
You know, I think in the past year,

00:28:04.410 --> 00:28:06.481
a lot of friends and
family are trying to say,

00:28:06.481 --> 00:28:08.138
"Hey, yeah. What Sal's doing is great."

00:28:08.138 --> 00:28:11.762
But I think if you go back 3-4 years ago,

00:28:11.762 --> 00:28:14.659
and I was kinda just going into the,

00:28:14.659 --> 00:28:15.854
sometimes the guest room,

00:28:15.854 --> 00:28:17.339
and eventually converted the closet,

00:28:17.339 --> 00:28:19.865
making these YouTube videos,

00:28:19.865 --> 00:28:21.582
a lot of them said, "What's Sal doing?

00:28:21.582 --> 00:28:23.530
"Why is he spending all
of his time doing this?"

00:28:23.530 --> 00:28:24.751
I had a lot of friends who
kind of like, you know,

00:28:24.751 --> 00:28:26.682
"This is kind of weird."

00:28:27.666 --> 00:28:28.909
Andrew: Tell me about how that felt,

00:28:28.909 --> 00:28:30.204
because it's easy to look back and say,

00:28:30.204 --> 00:28:31.618
"Eh, you know, that's what happened,

00:28:31.618 --> 00:28:32.527
"and we got through it."

00:28:32.527 --> 00:28:33.696
Tell me about how that felt so that

00:28:33.696 --> 00:28:35.741
when I have that situation in my life,

00:28:35.741 --> 00:28:37.470
or one of our listeners
has it in their lives,

00:28:37.470 --> 00:28:39.279
where they are just like 100 videos

00:28:39.279 --> 00:28:42.200
into a million-video project
the way you were back then,

00:28:42.200 --> 00:28:44.691
and no one believes in them
and they doubt themselves,

00:28:44.691 --> 00:28:46.235
they could identify with you.

00:28:46.235 --> 00:28:48.310
So what was it like for you?

00:28:48.310 --> 00:28:51.340
Salman: You know, I
think what allowed me to

00:28:51.340 --> 00:28:52.953
kind of keep up a high level of energy

00:28:52.953 --> 00:28:54.615
and stay motivated and want to do it

00:28:54.615 --> 00:28:58.651
is that I didn't care if it
ever got to where it did get.

00:28:58.651 --> 00:29:00.404
I was pretty happy with the,

00:29:00.404 --> 00:29:01.577
I guess you could call
them small successes.

00:29:01.577 --> 00:29:04.859
I was excited that 20
people a day were watching,

00:29:04.859 --> 00:29:07.127
20 people who I didn't know
were learning math from me.

00:29:07.127 --> 00:29:12.207
The idea that even if I
were to get hit by a bus,

00:29:12.207 --> 00:29:13.829
20 people a day, even if
it didn't grow at all,

00:29:13.829 --> 00:29:15.250
would still learn math from me.

00:29:15.250 --> 00:29:17.872
That, to me, was a
pretty profound concept.

00:29:18.779 --> 00:29:20.748
For me, just a couple notes a day,

00:29:20.748 --> 00:29:24.323
and that idea were enough for me to say,

00:29:24.323 --> 00:29:26.485
"Hey, this is a project worth my time."

00:29:26.485 --> 00:29:32.181
I mean, it is, if at minimum,
no non-relatives watched it,

00:29:32.181 --> 00:29:34.908
but if my son, when he's 18 years old,

00:29:35.169 --> 00:29:38.540
is able to learn a little bit
of algebra or calculus from me,

00:29:38.540 --> 00:29:39.948
that by itself makes it worth it.

00:29:39.948 --> 00:29:41.811
I mean, that by itself
makes it a neat project.

00:29:41.811 --> 00:29:44.033
I think in those early days,

00:29:44.033 --> 00:29:50.110
I was just excited about the
small, that small impact.

00:29:50.110 --> 00:29:51.569
That was enough.

00:29:51.569 --> 00:29:54.504
Now, in the back of my
mind, it was growing.

00:29:54.504 --> 00:29:56.075
I said, "Well, if it keeps
growing at this rate,

00:29:56.075 --> 00:29:57.209
"Then right now, there's 20.

00:29:57.209 --> 00:29:58.674
"Next month there might be 30,

00:29:58.674 --> 00:30:00.300
"and, boy, in a year, we'd
have a couple thousand,

00:30:00.300 --> 00:30:01.329
"and in two years, you know ..."

00:30:01.329 --> 00:30:03.120
Exponential growth, it
happens pretty fast.

00:30:03.120 --> 00:30:06.205
So that, I was like,
that would just be gravy

00:30:06.205 --> 00:30:08.229
on top of everything else that happened.

00:30:08.536 --> 00:30:10.309
Andrew: Did you have a
moment where you doubted it?

00:30:10.309 --> 00:30:11.879
Where you were down on it?

00:30:11.879 --> 00:30:14.559
Where you said, "What am
I doing here in the closet

00:30:14.559 --> 00:30:16.706
"or on my computer, wherever it was?"

00:30:16.706 --> 00:30:18.390
Salman: You know, I never did,

00:30:18.390 --> 00:30:21.400
although I did have a lot of ...

00:30:22.132 --> 00:30:26.030
I never doubted it, and
I'll tell you one of the,

00:30:26.030 --> 00:30:29.172
I'm a bit of a stubborn
character, and I did early on

00:30:29.172 --> 00:30:34.472
have people say, "Who
do you think you are?"

00:30:34.472 --> 00:30:37.452
Like, you know, I've had
friends who are schoolteachers,

00:30:37.452 --> 00:30:39.117
who are academics.

00:30:39.117 --> 00:30:40.966
Not all of them, some of
them were very supportive.

00:30:40.966 --> 00:30:42.137
They thought it was cool.

00:30:42.137 --> 00:30:44.046
In general, I got kind
of negative push-back

00:30:44.046 --> 00:30:45.936
from people who never
experienced the videos.

00:30:45.936 --> 00:30:46.952
I think there's two camps.

00:30:46.952 --> 00:30:48.773
People who actually experienced the videos

00:30:48.773 --> 00:30:50.574
and said, "Wow, this is
kind of a cool way to learn.

00:30:50.574 --> 00:30:53.381
"It was strangely engaging
and strangely addictive.

00:30:53.381 --> 00:30:55.332
"It kind of got me excited about things,

00:30:55.332 --> 00:30:56.550
"and it was kind of entertaining."

00:30:56.550 --> 00:30:58.799
Those people are almost
universally supportive,

00:30:58.799 --> 00:31:01.636
but a very small subset of my,

00:31:01.636 --> 00:31:03.829
of people who were close
to me actually did that.

00:31:03.829 --> 00:31:07.101
They actually took the
time to experience them.

00:31:07.101 --> 00:31:08.799
A lot more people I know were like,

00:31:08.799 --> 00:31:13.052
you know, there's billions of
dollars being spent on education,

00:31:13.052 --> 00:31:16.507
there's thousands of people with PhDs

00:31:16.507 --> 00:31:19.006
spending their whole life on
fixing the education system,

00:31:19.006 --> 00:31:23.053
isn't it arrogant of you to think that you

00:31:23.053 --> 00:31:25.445
and your YouTube videos are
gonna have any type of impact?

00:31:25.445 --> 00:31:26.551
I mean, that's essentially the summary

00:31:26.551 --> 00:31:28.905
of what a lot of people would tell me.

00:31:30.627 --> 00:31:32.718
I would defend it a little bit at first.

00:31:32.718 --> 00:31:34.804
I'd be like, well, in the back of my mind,

00:31:34.804 --> 00:31:37.013
I would say, "Well, I think
a lot of those efforts there

00:31:37.013 --> 00:31:38.569
are just spent on bureaucracies

00:31:38.569 --> 00:31:39.836
and people talking about things,

00:31:39.836 --> 00:31:41.418
but I wouldn't say that.

00:31:41.418 --> 00:31:43.207
My response was, "Well,
you know, you're right.

00:31:43.207 --> 00:31:44.306
"I don't think it's gonna, you know,

00:31:44.306 --> 00:31:45.709
"I just wanna do my
own little small thing.

00:31:45.709 --> 00:31:47.306
"If it has any impact, it has an impact,"

00:31:47.306 --> 00:31:49.486
but in the back of my mind
it made me really angry,

00:31:49.486 --> 00:31:51.339
and it motivated me even more

00:31:51.339 --> 00:31:56.442
to make more and better
videos, and to do it.

00:31:57.641 --> 00:31:59.267
To some degree, that's what,

00:32:00.067 --> 00:32:01.865
like the history videos you talked about.

00:32:01.865 --> 00:32:05.933
Every time I meet a small set of videos,

00:32:05.933 --> 00:32:07.129
I started with pre-algebra and algebra,

00:32:07.129 --> 00:32:08.146
I'd always get some push back.

00:32:08.146 --> 00:32:09.562
"Oh yeah, that's nice and
cute what you have there,

00:32:09.562 --> 00:32:12.771
"but this won't work for calculus,

00:32:12.771 --> 00:32:15.488
"or this won't work for
differential equations or physics,"

00:32:15.488 --> 00:32:17.560
and I'm going, "Oh, maybe you're right."

00:32:17.560 --> 00:32:18.472
But then I'd go home, and it's like,

00:32:18.472 --> 00:32:19.241
"I'm gonna show that person.

00:32:19.241 --> 00:32:21.435
"I'm gonna fix up the calculus
and the differential equations."

00:32:21.435 --> 00:32:23.566
Then you immediately get the push back,

00:32:23.566 --> 00:32:24.776
"Oh, this might work for that,

00:32:24.776 --> 00:32:26.182
"but it won't work for the humanities,

00:32:26.182 --> 00:32:27.842
"it won't work, and you
won't be able to do that.

00:32:27.842 --> 00:32:28.947
"You're gonna have to get other people."

00:32:28.947 --> 00:32:31.268
I mean it's amazing how
many people still tell me,

00:32:32.313 --> 00:32:33.898
"So, you're gonna have
to get more people on."

00:32:33.898 --> 00:32:36.267
I'm open to it. I'm not
like against getting others.

00:32:36.267 --> 00:32:37.230
In fact, when I started,

00:32:37.230 --> 00:32:39.047
I thought that's how this would happen,

00:32:39.047 --> 00:32:41.636
that there'd be 20 of us doing a large,

00:32:41.636 --> 00:32:42.902
but it was actually hard to.

00:32:42.902 --> 00:32:44.574
A lot of people would say,
"Yeah, that's awesome."

00:32:44.574 --> 00:32:46.106
At parties, they'd be like,
"Yeah, I want to make videos,

00:32:46.106 --> 00:32:47.446
"and that would be so cool,"

00:32:47.446 --> 00:32:49.095
but when it actually comes
down to actually sitting down

00:32:49.095 --> 00:32:51.353
with the tablet and
recording YouTube videos,

00:32:51.353 --> 00:32:53.610
no one really did it.

00:32:53.610 --> 00:32:56.212
Even now, there's a lot
of assumption of like,

00:32:56.212 --> 00:33:00.032
"Oh, well, you're not gonna
be able to do all of K-12,"

00:33:00.032 --> 00:33:03.364
and I'm like, "Part time, for 4 years,

00:33:03.364 --> 00:33:06.642
"you know, I was working in a
hedge fund most of the time.

00:33:07.734 --> 00:33:11.459
"It's pretty much 90% of
K-12 math has been done.

00:33:11.459 --> 00:33:13.205
"If you extrapolate that full-time,

00:33:13.205 --> 00:33:14.431
"it's not gonna take long to do it."

00:33:14.431 --> 00:33:16.409
I'm not gonna say I'm the
only person that has to.

00:33:16.409 --> 00:33:18.042
I actually want other people to do this,

00:33:18.042 --> 00:33:19.772
but they're not doing it,

00:33:19.772 --> 00:33:22.139
so if they're not doing it,
and I want to do it anyways,

00:33:22.139 --> 00:33:23.659
so I'm gonna do it.

00:33:25.104 --> 00:33:27.675
It is a bit of a motivating force

00:33:27.675 --> 00:33:30.241
when people kind of question your validity

00:33:30.241 --> 00:33:32.928
or your ability to execute on something.

00:33:32.928 --> 00:33:35.999
It ignites a little fire
in my belly a little bit.

00:33:35.999 --> 00:33:37.025
(laughs)

00:33:37.025 --> 00:33:37.661
Andrew: Yeah, I've seen that.

00:33:37.661 --> 00:33:39.626
I've felt that in myself, too.

00:33:40.610 --> 00:33:41.795
All right, so how do you do it?

00:33:41.795 --> 00:33:42.862
How do you do it so well?

00:33:42.862 --> 00:33:43.717
Let me just ...

00:33:43.717 --> 00:33:45.553
Actually, why don't you
start out by describing it?

00:33:45.553 --> 00:33:47.143
Maybe I should have done that
earlier in the interview,

00:33:47.143 --> 00:33:51.163
but I think, why don't we start
out with you describing it first?

00:33:52.039 --> 00:33:54.302
Salman: Yeah, you know, the
videos, you don't see me.

00:33:54.302 --> 00:33:56.112
They're black background
almost universally.

00:33:56.112 --> 00:33:57.436
Some of them don't have black backgrounds,

00:33:57.436 --> 00:33:58.663
but they have black backgrounds,

00:33:58.663 --> 00:34:01.644
and I'm just writing in
colors that I think look nice

00:34:02.352 --> 00:34:04.866
while I talk, while I narrate the video,

00:34:04.866 --> 00:34:07.902
and the form factor started, two things,

00:34:07.902 --> 00:34:09.580
this was essentially what
Nadia was experiencing

00:34:09.580 --> 00:34:13.025
when I was doing those initial
live virtual sessions with her.

00:34:13.025 --> 00:34:13.903
She didn't see me.

00:34:13.903 --> 00:34:15.179
We just had a conference call going,

00:34:15.179 --> 00:34:17.150
and she just saw what I was writing,

00:34:17.150 --> 00:34:17.921
and so it worked with her,

00:34:17.921 --> 00:34:19.336
so I said that'll probably work.

00:34:19.336 --> 00:34:23.623
I also wanted it to, I didn't
have good recording equipment.

00:34:23.623 --> 00:34:25.297
I didn't have a video camera.

00:34:25.297 --> 00:34:27.483
Even if I did, I even
thought about at one point,

00:34:27.483 --> 00:34:30.080
maybe buying one, but
it's really difficult.

00:34:30.080 --> 00:34:31.294
Even if you get a really
nice video camera,

00:34:31.294 --> 00:34:32.705
you have to get your lighting right,

00:34:32.705 --> 00:34:34.182
then you have to get your own microphone.

00:34:34.182 --> 00:34:35.491
I mean, all sorts of crazy
things you have to do

00:34:35.491 --> 00:34:36.823
to make it look professional,

00:34:36.823 --> 00:34:39.242
but if you just do a screen capture

00:34:39.242 --> 00:34:40.628
with a USB headset,

00:34:40.628 --> 00:34:42.188
and I started with Microsoft Paint,

00:34:42.188 --> 00:34:43.809
and now I'm using little fancier stuff,

00:34:43.809 --> 00:34:46.521
but it's all, I'm still
using Smooth Draw 3.

00:34:46.521 --> 00:34:48.859
It's a piece of freeware.

00:34:48.859 --> 00:34:51.330
It comes off a lot better,

00:34:51.330 --> 00:34:54.111
and the feedback I get from people,

00:34:54.111 --> 00:34:56.415
and it's kind of obvious now in hindsight,

00:34:56.415 --> 00:34:58.325
that it's actually much
more intimate form factor.

00:34:58.325 --> 00:35:00.823
It doesn't feel like I'm
on the other side of a room

00:35:00.823 --> 00:35:02.207
lecturing to you.

00:35:02.207 --> 00:35:03.857
It literally feels like we're
either beside each other,

00:35:03.857 --> 00:35:05.987
and we're looking at the same blackboard

00:35:05.987 --> 00:35:06.980
or the same piece of paper,

00:35:06.980 --> 00:35:10.352
or it even feels like I'm, what
my narration is your thoughts

00:35:10.352 --> 00:35:12.011
on some level.

00:35:14.072 --> 00:35:17.619
So the form factor both,
I think, is compelling

00:35:17.619 --> 00:35:20.412
to a lot of students, and
it's really easy for me.

00:35:20.412 --> 00:35:23.309
I literally just have to press record,

00:35:23.309 --> 00:35:25.281
start the screen capture going.

00:35:25.281 --> 00:35:26.378
I don't have to comb my hair.

00:35:26.378 --> 00:35:27.370
I don't have to shave.

00:35:27.370 --> 00:35:28.720
I don't have to do anything,

00:35:28.720 --> 00:35:33.317
and I just start talking
and start teaching.

00:35:33.317 --> 00:35:34.190
The question of how I do it,

00:35:34.190 --> 00:35:37.020
things like a lot of the algebra content,

00:35:37.020 --> 00:35:40.792
I do a lot of that in real
time, very conversational,

00:35:40.792 --> 00:35:42.341
a lot of the example problems I do,

00:35:42.341 --> 00:35:45.258
in the early videos, I actually
made them up on the fly,

00:35:45.258 --> 00:35:48.051
which I realize that kind of
wastes a little bit of time,

00:35:48.051 --> 00:35:51.554
but I always do them on the fly,

00:35:51.554 --> 00:35:55.950
and I think that gives
students a lens into concepts

00:35:55.950 --> 00:35:57.090
that they don't normally see.

00:35:57.090 --> 00:35:59.812
I mean, in a textbook, or
in a traditional lecture,

00:35:59.812 --> 00:36:01.588
you always have a finished product,

00:36:01.588 --> 00:36:03.388
that the teacher is seeing the example,

00:36:03.388 --> 00:36:04.240
they've done the example.

00:36:04.240 --> 00:36:05.825
Maybe they've done it 6 times that day

00:36:05.825 --> 00:36:08.887
for the last 20 years,
and you never see them,

00:36:08.887 --> 00:36:10.796
you never see the art of the problem,

00:36:10.796 --> 00:36:12.258
and you never see it solved in real time,

00:36:12.258 --> 00:36:13.769
and I get a lot of feedback.

00:36:13.769 --> 00:36:16.286
Students like to see me go
down a little path and say,

00:36:16.286 --> 00:36:17.322
"Oh wait, wait. That's not right,

00:36:17.322 --> 00:36:19.110
"but I did it because it looked like that.

00:36:19.110 --> 00:36:20.850
"Let me back up and go
down this other path."

00:36:20.850 --> 00:36:23.847
They really appreciate that
informal conversational

00:36:23.847 --> 00:36:27.708
kind of thinking out loud style.

00:36:27.708 --> 00:36:30.834
For the more preparation-intensive topics,

00:36:30.834 --> 00:36:32.374
like when I did cellular respiration,

00:36:32.374 --> 00:36:34.920
or the French Revolution.

00:36:34.920 --> 00:36:35.818
These aren't things that,

00:36:35.818 --> 00:36:38.876
you know, I was exposed
to them in my education,

00:36:38.876 --> 00:36:40.062
but they weren't something
that I would, like,

00:36:40.062 --> 00:36:42.106
if you had bumped into
me 2 years ago and said,

00:36:42.106 --> 00:36:43.246
"Sal, tell me everything about,

00:36:43.246 --> 00:36:45.061
"tell me how many ATPs are
generated by this stage

00:36:45.061 --> 00:36:45.941
"of cellular respiration."

00:36:45.941 --> 00:36:48.570
I would have been like, "Well,
I took it a long time ago."

00:36:48.570 --> 00:36:50.055
Those type of things I
do spend a lot of time

00:36:50.055 --> 00:36:51.398
immersing myself in the subject matter.

00:36:51.398 --> 00:36:52.336
Andrew: So tell me about that.

00:36:52.336 --> 00:36:53.244
Tell me about the process.

00:36:53.244 --> 00:36:54.939
How do you absorb that knowledge,

00:36:54.939 --> 00:36:56.933
and then we'll get into how do you share

00:36:56.933 --> 00:36:58.545
a tough topic with someone else?

00:36:58.545 --> 00:36:59.233
How do teach it?

00:36:59.233 --> 00:37:02.019
How do you get the knowledge
in your head so quickly?

00:37:02.019 --> 00:37:06.969
Salman: You know, well, I try to,

00:37:07.676 --> 00:37:09.642
I just try to read as
many things as I can.

00:37:09.642 --> 00:37:11.601
I think, you know, to some degree,

00:37:11.601 --> 00:37:13.670
obviously Khan Academy
is dependent on the web.

00:37:13.670 --> 00:37:15.105
You'd need YouTube and all of that,

00:37:15.105 --> 00:37:17.235
but it also needed the
web for my own preparation

00:37:17.235 --> 00:37:19.428
because in kind of the old days,

00:37:19.428 --> 00:37:20.439
you'd only have one source.

00:37:20.439 --> 00:37:21.546
You'd have your textbook or whatever,

00:37:21.546 --> 00:37:23.704
and that's very limiting,

00:37:23.704 --> 00:37:27.199
but now you literally, you have textbooks,

00:37:27.199 --> 00:37:28.765
you have things like Wikipedia,

00:37:28.765 --> 00:37:31.150
you have random professors,
random people on the web,

00:37:31.150 --> 00:37:32.539
explaining concepts.

00:37:32.539 --> 00:37:34.592
You know, 90% of them are
explaining it the same way,

00:37:34.592 --> 00:37:36.371
but that 10%, they'll say something,

00:37:36.371 --> 00:37:37.311
and it just clicks in your brain,

00:37:37.311 --> 00:37:39.354
and it was like, "Oh, why
didn't everyone just say that?"

00:37:39.354 --> 00:37:40.329
That's the most,

00:37:40.329 --> 00:37:42.370
and then you have all
these other, you know,

00:37:42.370 --> 00:37:44.888
I'm actually a big fan of, I think,

00:37:44.888 --> 00:37:46.999
well, this is kind of a commentary
in the publishing industry.

00:37:46.999 --> 00:37:49.207
I think textbooks are
written not to teach.

00:37:49.207 --> 00:37:51.218
Textbooks are written
to impress school boards

00:37:51.218 --> 00:37:53.055
and to be these impressive, weighty,

00:37:53.055 --> 00:37:55.044
you know, tombs, as opposed to something

00:37:55.044 --> 00:37:56.613
that a student could digest.

00:37:56.613 --> 00:37:59.314
I actually think a lot of the, whatever,

00:37:59.314 --> 00:38:00.925
teach-yourself books that
you get in the library

00:38:00.925 --> 00:38:06.423
for $10 or the Barron's
Calculus the Easy Way,

00:38:06.423 --> 00:38:08.685
Biology the Easy Way, these
are actually really good texts.

00:38:08.685 --> 00:38:10.295
They shouldn't be downplayed.

00:38:10.295 --> 00:38:12.061
You start with something like that,

00:38:12.061 --> 00:38:13.733
and when you have questions, you're like,

00:38:13.733 --> 00:38:15.160
"Okay, that kind of gave me the overview,

00:38:15.160 --> 00:38:17.108
"but I still don't understand
exactly what happens

00:38:17.108 --> 00:38:19.025
"at this stage or that stage."

00:38:19.025 --> 00:38:20.941
Then you can use texts
as reference, dig deeper,

00:38:20.941 --> 00:38:22.503
use Wikipedia as a reference.

00:38:22.503 --> 00:38:25.311
Then when I really get to
some really core question,

00:38:25.311 --> 00:38:27.579
I was doing immunology,
which I'm not an expert in,

00:38:27.579 --> 00:38:31.912
and in one part of my
wife's immunology textbook,

00:38:31.912 --> 00:38:35.167
she's a doctor, so she has
her immunology textbook

00:38:35.167 --> 00:38:36.650
from medical school, and
I was digging through it.

00:38:36.650 --> 00:38:40.101
In one part of it, it
was saying, "B-cells,

00:38:40.101 --> 00:38:44.977
"they need to be exposed to
the antigen to be activated,"

00:38:44.977 --> 00:38:46.168
and then another part, it says,

00:38:46.168 --> 00:38:48.063
"Well, helper T-cells activate B-cells."

00:38:48.063 --> 00:38:49.240
I had these questions, I was like,

00:38:49.240 --> 00:38:51.746
does both have to happen,
or just one of them,

00:38:51.746 --> 00:38:53.469
and I couldn't find it anywhere.

00:38:53.469 --> 00:38:55.120
I couldn't find the answers, so I
literally just called up a friend

00:38:55.120 --> 00:38:59.298
whose a professor of virology
at Duke, and I asked him.

00:38:59.298 --> 00:39:00.874
I was like, "Look, I know this
is a really stupid question.

00:39:00.874 --> 00:39:02.106
"You're gonna judge
me, because you're like

00:39:02.106 --> 00:39:05.052
"why does Sal, I shouldn't
be doing immunology videos

00:39:05.052 --> 00:39:06.264
"if I don't know the
answer to this question,"

00:39:06.264 --> 00:39:07.166
and I asked him.

00:39:07.166 --> 00:39:08.084
I was like, which one?

00:39:08.084 --> 00:39:09.553
He's like, "Oh, that's actually
a very interesting question.

00:39:09.553 --> 00:39:10.719
"There are certain types of B-cells ..."

00:39:10.719 --> 00:39:13.662
and he's like, "It's an area
of research of why that is,"

00:39:13.662 --> 00:39:15.979
and this and that, and it's
completely not in the textbook.

00:39:15.979 --> 00:39:19.927
I think, very quickly, as
long as you're really kind of,

00:39:20.573 --> 00:39:22.153
if you're asking yourself
the right questions,

00:39:22.153 --> 00:39:24.852
and you really are focused
on getting down to a

00:39:24.852 --> 00:39:27.988
distilled intuition of a subject,

00:39:27.988 --> 00:39:30.298
it doesn't take long before
you can really get to

00:39:30.298 --> 00:39:31.705
kind of fundamental questions

00:39:31.705 --> 00:39:33.166
that even experts in the field say,

00:39:33.166 --> 00:39:34.320
"Hey, that's an interest ..."

00:39:34.320 --> 00:39:36.599
There's this other, I
talk to a lot of friends

00:39:36.599 --> 00:39:40.316
who have PhDs, are professors,
or doing PhDs, or whatever,

00:39:40.977 --> 00:39:43.072
and sometimes if I meet them at a party,

00:39:43.072 --> 00:39:44.961
I'm like, "Oh, you know,
I'm gonna do a video on this

00:39:44.961 --> 00:39:46.933
"probably next week, and I have this one

00:39:46.933 --> 00:39:49.159
"question about, it's like
a fundamental concept,

00:39:49.159 --> 00:39:51.976
"something that a first-year
grad student should know."

00:39:51.976 --> 00:39:53.790
And they're like, "You know what?

00:39:54.297 --> 00:39:56.807
"That's something I always wondered,

00:39:56.807 --> 00:40:00.532
"but I didn't really have time
to address it in my education,

00:40:00.532 --> 00:40:02.184
"and I had qualifiers to pass,

00:40:02.184 --> 00:40:04.193
"and I was probably
embarrassed to even bring it up

00:40:04.193 --> 00:40:07.300
"inside of my department, and so

00:40:07.300 --> 00:40:08.562
"I really don't know the answer to that."

00:40:08.562 --> 00:40:10.356
One, that makes me feel a lot better,

00:40:10.356 --> 00:40:12.296
but then we would kind of
become on a mission combined

00:40:12.296 --> 00:40:13.400
to get that question answered,

00:40:13.400 --> 00:40:15.508
and I would be kind of their
layperson that would say,

00:40:15.508 --> 00:40:16.501
"Hey, this guy's wondering, you know,"

00:40:16.501 --> 00:40:23.225
so if you want to know where
I think I'm adding value

00:40:23.225 --> 00:40:25.541
beyond people who have
spent more time in the field

00:40:25.541 --> 00:40:28.993
is that I have the luxury
of spending as much time

00:40:28.993 --> 00:40:31.740
as I want on core concepts,

00:40:31.740 --> 00:40:33.300
and I think core concepts
are the most important

00:40:33.300 --> 00:40:35.062
because that's where you build
your intuition of a subject.

00:40:35.062 --> 00:40:37.010
When I started chemistry,
before I even started,

00:40:37.010 --> 00:40:39.910
I just played with the
Periodic Table for like a week,

00:40:39.910 --> 00:40:41.164
just to make sure I understood the nuance,

00:40:41.164 --> 00:40:42.822
why was it structured that way,

00:40:42.822 --> 00:40:43.632
why is the pattern,

00:40:43.632 --> 00:40:46.535
how did it come about,

00:40:46.535 --> 00:40:48.749
as opposed to it's just there,
and how do you interpret it?

00:40:48.749 --> 00:40:50.486
How did the first people even think

00:40:50.486 --> 00:40:52.778
of making a periodic table
and things like that.

00:40:53.239 --> 00:40:56.971
I get that luxury, and
PhDs and grad students

00:40:56.971 --> 00:40:58.516
and professors don't have that luxury

00:40:58.516 --> 00:41:01.709
of really understanding the core.

00:41:01.709 --> 00:41:02.763
You know, a friend of mine,

00:41:02.763 --> 00:41:04.641
I haven't done quantum
mechanics videos yet,

00:41:04.641 --> 00:41:06.690
and I had a friend who was
explaining to me a little bit,

00:41:06.690 --> 00:41:07.454
and he was like, "Oh, yeah.

00:41:07.454 --> 00:41:10.327
"If you have this electron,
it's moving in this chamber,

00:41:10.327 --> 00:41:11.291
this theoretical chamber,"

00:41:11.291 --> 00:41:14.027
and I was like, "Oh, why
is it changing direction?"

00:41:14.027 --> 00:41:16.710
He's like, "That's a good question."

00:41:16.710 --> 00:41:18.320
I mean, it's like one of
these fundamental examples

00:41:18.320 --> 00:41:21.421
that every first-year quantum
mechanics student learns,

00:41:21.421 --> 00:41:23.096
and the teacher doesn't go over that.

00:41:23.096 --> 00:41:25.653
They just say, "Oh,"
and they give equation,

00:41:25.653 --> 00:41:27.302
and you kind of learn to mimic
in and so on and so forth,

00:41:27.302 --> 00:41:29.966
but everyone's afraid to ask
these very basic questions.

00:41:29.966 --> 00:41:32.081
I ask them, eventually
I get an answer to them,

00:41:32.081 --> 00:41:34.628
and I think when I teach it,
I'll answer those questions,

00:41:34.628 --> 00:41:36.666
and then people don't have
those gaps in their head.

00:41:36.666 --> 00:41:38.111
Andrew: It seems like the Khan Academy

00:41:38.111 --> 00:41:42.704
is great for teaching
Khan, for teaching you,

00:41:42.704 --> 00:41:45.532
because you now are going
through the ideal university.

00:41:45.532 --> 00:41:49.750
Can you talk about how knowing
that you're going to teach

00:41:49.750 --> 00:41:52.751
what you're learning affects
what you're learning?

00:41:52.751 --> 00:41:54.133
Salman: Oh, yeah.

00:41:54.702 --> 00:41:57.315
Well, you know, it puts
the bar so much higher.

00:41:57.315 --> 00:41:59.343
I mean, I think in most,
like I'm gonna start doing

00:41:59.343 --> 00:42:00.725
organic chemistry soon,

00:42:00.725 --> 00:42:02.368
and when you're taking organic chemistry,

00:42:02.368 --> 00:42:04.206
and I took organic chemistry in college.

00:42:04.206 --> 00:42:06.426
You're goal is really to get an A,

00:42:06.426 --> 00:42:09.614
and if you're especially
intellectually inspired,

00:42:09.614 --> 00:42:11.714
maybe to get another
level of understanding,

00:42:11.714 --> 00:42:13.821
but there's all these other pressures

00:42:13.821 --> 00:42:15.299
that are going on in college,

00:42:15.299 --> 00:42:17.397
your grades and social
pressures and other classes

00:42:17.397 --> 00:42:18.351
and all of that,

00:42:18.351 --> 00:42:21.618
and now, I know I'm gonna explain it,

00:42:21.618 --> 00:42:24.513
and I know, from the math
videos, there's a certain brand,

00:42:24.513 --> 00:42:26.257
there's a certain standard
that people expect,

00:42:26.257 --> 00:42:27.933
that I'm not just gonna
throw something at you

00:42:27.933 --> 00:42:29.413
and say memorize this,

00:42:29.413 --> 00:42:31.531
or I'm not just gonna say,
like, "Oh, this is beyond you.

00:42:31.531 --> 00:42:32.588
"Don't try to understand it."

00:42:32.588 --> 00:42:35.362
The standard people expect from me

00:42:35.362 --> 00:42:37.319
is that I will give them an intuition,

00:42:37.319 --> 00:42:39.022
and I will distill it down into concepts

00:42:39.022 --> 00:42:40.484
where people say, "Oh
wait, that's obvious.

00:42:40.484 --> 00:42:42.528
"That's all that thing is
saying about the universe."

00:42:42.528 --> 00:42:45.602
And so that's the standard I
hold myself to when I learn it,

00:42:45.602 --> 00:42:48.409
so it doesn't take long,
actually, to learn something

00:42:48.409 --> 00:42:50.630
of a level where you can
get an A on most exams

00:42:50.630 --> 00:42:54.060
at most schools, but
it's a whole other level

00:42:54.060 --> 00:42:55.736
where you're getting to the really deep,

00:42:55.736 --> 00:42:57.185
why is this intuitive,

00:42:57.185 --> 00:42:59.182
or why does that expression
look the way it does,

00:42:59.182 --> 00:43:00.925
or how is it related
to another expression?

00:43:00.925 --> 00:43:02.560
It's hugely motivating while I'm learning.

00:43:02.560 --> 00:43:06.951
I mean, it keeps me
going a little bit deeper

00:43:06.951 --> 00:43:08.668
than I think most anyone would

00:43:08.668 --> 00:43:11.725
if they were just doing it
for getting a credential.

00:43:11.725 --> 00:43:15.318
Andrew: Don't medical
schools teach by showing,

00:43:15.318 --> 00:43:18.884
doing teaching method, where
the student gets to learn it,

00:43:18.884 --> 00:43:21.581
gets to do it, and then has
to teach it to someone else

00:43:21.581 --> 00:43:24.087
because when you teach
it, you really absorb it?

00:43:24.087 --> 00:43:27.336
Salman: Yeah. No, and I'm
a huge believer in that.

00:43:27.336 --> 00:43:28.911
I mean, that's, you know, when
I talk about the virtual school.

00:43:28.911 --> 00:43:32.280
That's why I think the
peer to peer is huge.

00:43:32.280 --> 00:43:34.941
I think mastery comes
not just from being able

00:43:34.941 --> 00:43:35.582
to do a lot of problems.

00:43:35.582 --> 00:43:37.528
It really comes from that
exercise of teaching it.

00:43:37.528 --> 00:43:39.169
I mean, I found it with my own experience,

00:43:39.169 --> 00:43:41.232
but if you have kids all over
the world teaching each other,

00:43:41.232 --> 00:43:42.604
and that's why you have
that 1-room schoolhouse

00:43:42.604 --> 00:43:43.387
all of a sudden,

00:43:43.387 --> 00:43:45.451
I think you're just gonna
have a whole other level

00:43:45.451 --> 00:43:47.560
of mastery that doesn't exist right now.

00:43:47.959 --> 00:43:49.334
Andrew: All right, so how do you teach?

00:43:49.334 --> 00:43:51.187
How do you teach tough topics?

00:43:51.756 --> 00:43:52.988
Teach us how to teach,

00:43:52.988 --> 00:43:54.786
because we're all gonna
have to teach our employees,

00:43:54.786 --> 00:43:56.705
we're gonna have to teach
people who we work with,

00:43:56.705 --> 00:43:59.437
we're gonna have to teach others online.

00:43:59.437 --> 00:44:00.186
Salman: Right.

00:44:00.186 --> 00:44:01.791
Well, you know, I think there's
a couple of things here.

00:44:01.791 --> 00:44:03.530
You brought up an
interesting point just now

00:44:03.530 --> 00:44:04.901
when you talk about teaching employees

00:44:04.901 --> 00:44:05.813
and teaching others.

00:44:05.813 --> 00:44:07.399
I'm actually advising some tech companies,

00:44:07.399 --> 00:44:09.566
where they want to build
Khan-type applications

00:44:09.566 --> 00:44:11.124
on their platform and this and that.

00:44:11.124 --> 00:44:14.095
At first, I was writing traditional specs,

00:44:14.095 --> 00:44:15.884
like you would expect a
product manager or whoever

00:44:15.884 --> 00:44:16.892
would write at a company.

00:44:16.892 --> 00:44:18.374
I was like, this is silly.
I make YouTube videos,

00:44:18.374 --> 00:44:21.064
why don't I just do YouTube specs?

00:44:21.064 --> 00:44:22.296
I would literally just make a screen shot,

00:44:22.296 --> 00:44:24.334
and I would just explain what
the interaction should look like,

00:44:24.334 --> 00:44:25.996
and it's 10 times better,

00:44:25.996 --> 00:44:27.247
so I think to a large degree,

00:44:27.247 --> 00:44:30.363
just the form factor makes it way better

00:44:30.363 --> 00:44:31.630
than if I were to write a white paper,

00:44:31.630 --> 00:44:34.572
write a spec, or even if I
were to sit at a whiteboard

00:44:34.572 --> 00:44:36.827
and use my hands and face to drive it.

00:44:36.827 --> 00:44:38.452
One, I think the form
factor of screen capture

00:44:38.452 --> 00:44:42.410
with hand-drawn writing
is pretty powerful.

00:44:42.410 --> 00:44:44.775
Some people told me that cognitively,

00:44:44.775 --> 00:44:47.001
just seeing typing or seeing
a powerpoint presentation

00:44:47.001 --> 00:44:48.309
doesn't really stimulate the brain,

00:44:48.309 --> 00:44:50.964
but seeing someone write
something handwritten

00:44:50.964 --> 00:44:54.312
actually does, and I
kind of feel like that.

00:44:54.312 --> 00:44:56.082
It's also easier for me to produce.

00:44:57.497 --> 00:45:00.587
Beyond that, I think there's,

00:45:01.111 --> 00:45:02.363
you know, what I do is

00:45:02.363 --> 00:45:05.842
just get as comfortable as you
possibly can with the subject,

00:45:05.842 --> 00:45:10.635
and once you get that comfort,
don't script the video.

00:45:10.635 --> 00:45:13.934
Make it as relaxing as possible,
have fun while you're doing it.

00:45:13.934 --> 00:45:15.485
There's actually a gentleman
who's going to start

00:45:15.485 --> 00:45:17.496
translating some of the videos into Urdu,

00:45:17.496 --> 00:45:20.513
and my one feedback, he
did some great videos,

00:45:21.728 --> 00:45:23.795
but I was like, have more fun.

00:45:23.795 --> 00:45:25.934
Energy carries over in our voice,

00:45:25.934 --> 00:45:27.411
especially when you don't see the face.

00:45:27.411 --> 00:45:29.280
You really have to have a
lot of energy in your voice,

00:45:29.280 --> 00:45:32.880
and if you're not having fun,
the student won't have fun.

00:45:32.880 --> 00:45:36.569
Have fun, be relaxed, but really
know what you're talking about.

00:45:36.569 --> 00:45:37.838
Like, don't throw out buzzwords

00:45:37.838 --> 00:45:40.783
without really knowing
what is going on behind it.

00:45:40.783 --> 00:45:41.916
If you're at a company,

00:45:41.916 --> 00:45:45.907
I actually think the
way Khan Academy teaches

00:45:45.907 --> 00:45:48.280
would actually be ideal
instead of whitepapers,

00:45:48.280 --> 00:45:51.942
instead of a lot of what
goes on inside of companies

00:45:51.942 --> 00:45:53.436
to teach people how to do things.

00:45:53.436 --> 00:45:56.260
Just teach your peers, and
teach it as it really is.

00:45:56.260 --> 00:45:58.626
Don't try to look smart yourself
by throwing out buzzwords

00:45:58.626 --> 00:46:00.122
that you don't necessarily understand,

00:46:00.122 --> 00:46:03.010
or that you heard someone
else you think is smart say.

00:46:03.010 --> 00:46:06.577
Just say it in as down-to-earth
of a style as you can.

00:46:06.577 --> 00:46:09.026
Be frank if there is something
that you don't understand,

00:46:09.379 --> 00:46:12.251
and I think people will
respond well to it.

00:46:12.251 --> 00:46:13.862
Andrew: What about the way
that you give background

00:46:13.862 --> 00:46:15.796
before you get into the subject?

00:46:15.796 --> 00:46:17.214
How do you do it?

00:46:17.814 --> 00:46:24.112
Salman: You know, I think
throughout this process

00:46:24.112 --> 00:46:25.102
of making 1,500 videos,

00:46:25.102 --> 00:46:27.021
I've gotten very good at
being a train of thought,

00:46:27.021 --> 00:46:29.008
and I think a lot of
people when they teach,

00:46:29.008 --> 00:46:30.295
they actually close down,

00:46:30.295 --> 00:46:31.808
they actually shut off
a lot of their thoughts

00:46:31.808 --> 00:46:33.293
that may be embarrassing,

00:46:33.293 --> 00:46:35.455
that like, you know,
but when I do a problem,

00:46:35.455 --> 00:46:37.507
there is a little bit of a
neuron that reminds yourself

00:46:37.507 --> 00:46:39.363
that a negative times a
negative is a positive,

00:46:39.363 --> 00:46:40.974
and maybe even remind
yourself why that is,

00:46:40.974 --> 00:46:42.894
and remind yourself, you
know, all of these things

00:46:42.894 --> 00:46:43.863
while you're doing a problem,

00:46:43.863 --> 00:46:47.061
and I lay all that stuff out there.

00:46:47.061 --> 00:46:49.835
Even if you're watching
the vector calculus videos,

00:46:49.835 --> 00:46:52.162
it's literally, I don't assume anything.

00:46:52.162 --> 00:46:53.714
I'm literally doing
stream of consciousness.

00:46:53.714 --> 00:46:55.257
Every thought that's going in my brain,

00:46:55.257 --> 00:46:57.662
you're actually getting on paper,

00:46:57.662 --> 00:47:01.374
so there's no skipped steps, if you will.

00:47:01.374 --> 00:47:02.468
I think there's that.

00:47:02.468 --> 00:47:05.638
Before I do the video, I
do try to really make sure

00:47:05.638 --> 00:47:07.544
I understand the big picture really well,

00:47:07.544 --> 00:47:09.247
and probably, what I think
you're talking about,

00:47:09.247 --> 00:47:10.510
where I give the background,

00:47:10.510 --> 00:47:12.570
that's me articulating the big picture,

00:47:12.570 --> 00:47:14.013
just so I have a framework in my head

00:47:14.013 --> 00:47:15.142
of what we're even doing.

00:47:15.142 --> 00:47:17.080
I think a lot of times, in all subjects,

00:47:17.080 --> 00:47:18.274
once you start getting into it,

00:47:18.274 --> 00:47:20.583
you almost forget what you're
doing in the first place,

00:47:20.583 --> 00:47:24.352
and while I'm doing it,
I like to remind myself,

00:47:24.352 --> 00:47:25.765
"What are we even doing?

00:47:25.765 --> 00:47:28.500
We're on step 50 of this equation.

00:47:28.500 --> 00:47:29.796
What was the whole point to begin with?

00:47:29.796 --> 00:47:31.502
It's good to remind yourself,

00:47:31.502 --> 00:47:33.039
it's good to remind
yourself from the beginning.

00:47:33.039 --> 00:47:34.988
It's not some artificial
teaching technique.

00:47:34.988 --> 00:47:36.273
It's literally, I'm reminding myself.

00:47:36.273 --> 00:47:37.858
I'm reminding myself this is why

00:47:37.858 --> 00:47:39.077
we're doing this problem right now,

00:47:39.077 --> 00:47:40.813
and I think it's valuable for the student.

00:47:40.813 --> 00:47:42.901
I think whatever keeps my energy level up

00:47:42.901 --> 00:47:45.041
while I do the video, will
also keep up the engagement

00:47:45.041 --> 00:47:47.222
and the energy level of the
person observing the video.

00:47:47.222 --> 00:47:48.077
Andrew: I see.

00:47:48.077 --> 00:47:50.548
People have to get that French Revolution.

00:47:50.548 --> 00:47:53.209
I can recommend it before I've
even finished watching it.

00:47:53.209 --> 00:47:54.155
It was so good.

00:47:54.155 --> 00:47:55.450
You even gave us a
little bit of background,

00:47:55.450 --> 00:47:59.110
and you said, "Well, the
French supported America,

00:47:59.110 --> 00:48:01.496
"in the American Revolution,"
and I just thought,

00:48:01.496 --> 00:48:02.967
wow, I wouldn't have
even thought to include

00:48:02.967 --> 00:48:04.197
something like that, but
it really does help me

00:48:04.197 --> 00:48:07.315
understand what's about to happen here.

00:48:08.268 --> 00:48:09.825
It does, it's a great reminder.

00:48:10.517 --> 00:48:13.542
How do you make it feel
interactive, when it's just you

00:48:13.542 --> 00:48:16.305
and it's not even your face in the video,

00:48:16.305 --> 00:48:19.389
how do you make it feel like
you're engaging the person?

00:48:20.189 --> 00:48:22.396
Well, you know, I think
there's a couple of things.

00:48:22.396 --> 00:48:24.569
I think, once again, we
talked about the form factor,

00:48:24.569 --> 00:48:25.970
how it looks, but it's also the videos are

00:48:25.970 --> 00:48:27.118
on average 10 minutes.

00:48:27.118 --> 00:48:28.709
These history videos go a
little bit longer than that.

00:48:29.724 --> 00:48:31.145
But I think because it's 10 minutes,

00:48:31.145 --> 00:48:33.958
the person goes into that
video wanting that video.

00:48:34.250 --> 00:48:36.034
It's not like they're
getting a 90-minute lecture

00:48:36.034 --> 00:48:38.796
which may engage them for part of it.

00:48:38.796 --> 00:48:41.639
I mean, it's almost like, the
act of clicking on a video

00:48:41.639 --> 00:48:43.152
is almost like asking a question.

00:48:43.152 --> 00:48:45.929
Like, "Tell me more about
the French Revolution,"

00:48:45.929 --> 00:48:48.971
or, "Tell me more about
Napoleonic Campaigns in Russia,"

00:48:48.971 --> 00:48:50.748
and so it's literally just addressing

00:48:50.748 --> 00:48:52.754
that exact need you have right there,

00:48:52.754 --> 00:48:53.930
and I think the other thing's just,

00:48:53.930 --> 00:48:55.368
you know, I think it's the form factor.

00:48:55.368 --> 00:48:56.454
it's a little bit of my tone.

00:48:56.454 --> 00:48:57.245
I'm conversational.

00:48:57.245 --> 00:48:59.761
I mean, literally, the
tone I use in the video

00:48:59.761 --> 00:49:01.924
is not at all different than
the tone I'm using right now.

00:49:01.924 --> 00:49:04.125
it's not at all like a lecture.

00:49:04.125 --> 00:49:05.206
"The next step in this,"

00:49:05.206 --> 00:49:06.506
it's not that at all.

00:49:07.121 --> 00:49:09.309
Andrew: How many of them do you do a day?

00:49:09.309 --> 00:49:10.131
Salman: It depends what I'm doing.

00:49:10.131 --> 00:49:12.363
When I was doing French Revolution

00:49:12.363 --> 00:49:14.291
or when I'm doing some of the more complex

